Wash and dry produce. Remove and discard any large stems from @kale{4%ounce}; finely chop leaves. Peel and thinly slice @garlic{2%clove}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #medium pan{} over medium-high heat (use a #large pan{} for 4 servings). Add kale, garlic, @water{2%TBSP} (3 TBSP for 4), and a big pinch of @salt{pinch}. Cook, covered, until kale begins to wilt, ~{2-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Uncover and stir occasionally to make sure kale doesn't stick to bottom of pan.

Transfer kale to a #small bowl{}.

Heat another drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @Italian chicken sausage mix{9%ounce}; using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer. Cook, without stirring, until browned on bottom, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @tomato paste{1.5%ounce} and half the @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon} (all for 4). Cook, breaking up sausage into pieces, until browned, ~{1-2%minutes} more (it'll finish cooking later).

Stir kale, @Israeli couscous{3/4%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and @water{1.5%cups} (3 cups for 4 servings) into pan with sausage. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to medium-high; simmer until couscous is tender and liquid has mostly absorbed, ~{6-8%minutes}.

> It's OK if there's still a small amount of liquid.

Once couscous is tender, stir @sour cream{2%tablespoon} and @butter{2%tablespoon} (4 TBSP for 4 servings) into pan until melted and combined. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: Add a small splash of water if couscous seems dry.

Sprinkle with @Italian cheese blend{1/2%cup}; cover pan until cheese melts, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Divide between plates or serve directly from pan.